8. What is a volatile variable? When should it be used, how does it differ from?
-->In Java, a volatile variable is a special field modifier that ensures any thread reading the variable always sees the most recent 
    value written by another thread. 
    
    What it is
    The volatile keyword tells the Java Virtual Machine (JVM) and the CPU to not cache the variable in local thread memory (CPU registers 
        or caches). Instead, every read and write operation is performed directly on the main memory (RAM). This guarantees visibility—the 
        certainty that updates made by one thread are immediately seen by others. 



